{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611836"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:16:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:16:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16249"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16249"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.92,0.04,0,0,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8940"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65151"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8940"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16249"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50587"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7086"},{"type":"tags","id":"10486"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21275"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21279"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65151"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe kidney undergoes various structural and functional changes with advancing age.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes changes that occur to renal function with normal aging?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Progressive glomerulosclerosis","Increased renal blood flow","Increased glomerular filtration rate","Increased number of functioning nephrons","Enhanced tubular secretory capacity"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWith aging, there is \u003Cstrong\u003Eprogressive glomerulosclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E leading to a decline in renal function. This is accompanied by a decrease in renal mass, reduced number of functioning nephrons, and decreased glomerular filtration rate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased renal blood flow\u003C/strong\u003E - Renal blood flow actually decreases with age by approximately 10% per decade after age 40, largely due to a decrease in cardiac output and structural changes in the vasculature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased glomerular filtration rate\u003C/strong\u003E - GFR declines by approximately 1 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 per year after age 40. This decline is due to factors such as decreased nephron function, reduced renal blood flow, and glomerulosclerosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased number of functioning nephrons\u003C/strong\u003E - The number of functioning nephrons decreases with age\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhanced tubular secretory capacity\u003C/strong\u003E - The tubular secretory capacity, which involves the kidney\u0027s ability to secrete certain substances like drugs and metabolic waste products, decreases with age. This results in slower elimination of some substances.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese age-related changes contribute to reduced renal reserve capacity and increased susceptibility to acute kidney injury in older adults.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Aging causes progressive glomerulosclerosis and decline in renal function.","Renal blood flow decreases by approximately 10% per decade after 